@node INTRO "Introduction"

			@{b}Introduction!@{ub}

    More observant Amiga users may have noticed that Windows 95 has
    a nice little bar at the bottom of the screen called the Taskbar.
    This bar allows you to switch between active programs.

    Although I prefer AmigaDos to WimpDos (Windows) I rather liked the
    taskbar and so I decided to write an Amiga version. I hope you
    like it.

    TaskBar is Freeware. You may use it and distribute it freely, but if
    you like it, pass it on.
@endnode

@node Features "Features"
		     @{b}Features!@{ub}

	    Completely font and screenmode sensitive
	    Can open on ANY public screen
	    Can maximise windows
	    Can panel windows horizontally
	    Can panel windows vertically
	    Can minimise windows
	    Preferences editor
	    Add items to Start Menu from an installer script
	    Uses resource tracking to close windows if it crashes
	    Recognises new windows when opened
	    Notices when windows close
	    Notices when windows change their names
	    Start button to launch programs
	    Nameless windows given name of owner task
	    Customerisable number of buttons
	    Configurable width or auto-sensing
	    Customerisable length of button strings


Many of the features of TaskBar were suggested by users.
If you have a suggestion or just want to say you like TaskBar
(always appreciated) then @{"contact me" link author}.

@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"
		  @{b}Installation!@{ub}

There is an installer script supplied for installing taskbar6, but if you
want to install it manually hereis how.


To make TaskBar start automatically.

> Simply copy @{b}TaskBar@{ub} and @{b}TaskBar.info@{ub}
 into WBStartup or wherever you want in your path,
 and then copy 'TaskBar4.prefs' into ENV: and ENVARC:

 If you have WB2.0 you can just drag the icon into the WBStartup drawer
 and drag the prefs file into ENVARC: (usually in prefs)

> If you want to launch taskbar from user startup then add the following to
 s:User-Startup.
 @{b}cd [where taskbar is]
 @{b}run <>NIL: Taskbar@{ub}



If you want to be able to edit TaskBar's preferences with the prefs editor
(as opposed to editing the config file by hand) then you must copy
TaskBarPrefs and TaskBarPrefs.info to Sys:Prefs.

If you do not do this then the 'Edit Preferences' option from TaskBar
will not work.

To launch programs as if from workbench, TaskBar uses WBRun. WBRun is
included in the TaskBar distribution.
				   

@endnode

@node Functions "Functions"
		  @{b}Functions!@{ub}

@{b}Amiga Taskbar can bring to front, minimise, maximise and panel any
 windows on the workbench screen.@{ub}

TaskBar uses a set of qualifiers to manage windows. While it can take
a while to learn them, it lets you work with windows very fast.


@{b}Bring to Front@{ub}
> Simply left click on the window's button.

@{b}Maximise@{ub}
> Click on the window's button with the right mouse button held down

@{b}Horizontally Maximise@{ub}
> Click on a button with the left shift key held down.

@{b}Panel@{ub}
> Click on both windows' buttons with the right mouse button held down
    If you hold down the left shift key then panel will be vertical.

@{b}Minimise@{ub}
> Click on a button with the right shift key held down.

@{b}Shrink or Grow TaskBar@{ub}
> Click on the start button with the right mouse button held down

@{b}Select a non listed window.@{ub}
> Click on @{b}Other@{ub} and a button can be created for a window

@{b}Change the number of buttons.@{ub}
> Select the Icon from Workbench and enter your desired number as
the value for the @{b}BUTTONS@{ub} tooltype. For a normal Hires or DblPal 
screen I recommend 4 or 6 buttons.

@{b}Force TaskBar to use button names of a preset length.@{ub}
> Change the @{b}MAXCHARS@{ub} tooltype. To let TaskBar make an educated 
guess (normal) bracket out the tooltype.

@{b}Force the width to a set value.@{ub} @{i}(eg if using Autoscroll)@{ui}
> Change the @{b}FIXWIDTH@{ub} tooltype Bracket it out for full screen

@{b}Quit.@{ub} @{i}( But why ? )@{ui}
>Select the window. If you want to be sure not to click on a button,
then use the right mouse button. Once the window is selected hit a key.

@{b}Launch a program.@{ub}
> Click @{b}Start@{ub} then select your desired program

@{b}Add a program to the start menu.@{ub}
> Select TaskBar/"Edit Preferences" from the Start popup.
  Click @{"here" link prefs} for more info on setting prefs.

@{b}Look at the example file and you will see what I mean.@{ub}
For further information about preferences read the @{"preferences" link prefs} section.

@endnode

@node Troubleshooting
		@{b}Troubleshooting!@{ub}

@{b}Sometimes taskbar quits itself without me telling it to@{ub}
> TaskBar uses a smart resource tracking system so that if it falls over
  (usually due to another task having a corrupt window) it closes all it's
  windows and libraries etc. If you know what window upset taskbar you can
  try adding it to the AVOID list.
    (Note that this may not always work as taskbar may fall over while
    trying to find out if it should avoid the window)

@{b}Some programs I launch from TaskBar do not launch correctly.
> Some programs need to be run as if from workbench. To do this you
  must use the shareware program WBRun. If you use Wbrun then you must
  put it in the CMD statement of the prefs file. eg
    CMD:WBRun ProPage instead of CMD:ProPage

@{b}The text overflows from the buttons and looks messy.@{ub}
> Set the MAXCHARS tooltype to your desired name length.
  The default value is only suitable for a screen width or 640 and
  a font of Topaz 8. If your settings are different then this tooltype
  MUST BE CHANGED. 

@{b}Nothing appears on my buttons when I launch TaskBAr from a script@{ub}
> Make sure that you cd to the TaskBAr directory before launching TaskBar
  or it can't find it's icon.

@{b}Opening TaskBar on some screens causes a crash or other problems@{ub}
> Some badly coded programs don't like other programs opening windows on
  their screens. UYou will just have to not open on these screens.

@{b}When my selected program is launched from the start button, it can't
find it's files.@{ub}
> Set the start item's DIR sttribute to the correct directory.

@{b}TaskBar says it can't find TaskBar.prefs.@{ub}
> Then you have to check if you got the TaskBar.prefs file in ENV: and ENVARC:
 or if you got something wrong with your path.

@{b}I can't select the TaskBar because I keep clicking on buttons.@{ub}
> Select it with the right mouse button.

@{b}I have MagicMenu and this stops TaskBar from sensing my right mouse button.@{ub}
> First select TaskBar with the Right Mouse Button.
 Then do whatever you want to do.
 MagicMenu will not interfere when TaskBar is selected.

@{b}When a window changes it's title, TaskBar doesn't notice.@{ub}
> To make TaskBar look at a window again, simply reselect it.

@{b}TaskBar misses off the first or last few characters of a window's title@{ub}
> It has to do this in order to fit it on the button.
  TaskBar decides whether the start or end of the title is most
  important automatically.

@{b}Some windows need to be maximised twice for it to work properly.@{ub}
> This is the fault of the window owner, not taskbar.
  While it is changing size it doesn't notice the message I have sent it
  to move to a new position.

@{b}TaskBar doesn't work properly with the new prefs file I have written.
> If you send me the file by email I should be able to show you what
  you have done wrong in your prefs file.


If you have any problems not solved by this page then MAIL ME!
If you have problems then I really do want to know about them.


@endnode

@node Changes

       @{b}Changes since v6@{ub}

> Bugfixes in TaskBarPrefs GUI

> Removed harmless enforcer hit in AUTOSHIFT


       @{b}Changes in v6 from v5.3@{ub}

> Preferences editor - by Guilherme Cirne

> Start popup reorganised

> Minimise All windows
    Useful for clearing up cluttered screens.

> Shift windows
    Move or resize windows so they don't overlap with the taskbar.

> Reload prefs
    For use with preferences editor

> Multiple screen support made more stable (thanks to Guilherme again)
    Now works on more screens

> Screen switching is faster

> Bug in start menu that caused occasional ignorance of selections fixed
    Thanks to the many people who spotted this one

> No longer interrupts drag and drop operations when active window changes.

> AutoFront made switchable. Default is off as AutoShift does all you need.



> Other little tweaks and alterations


@endnode

@node Problems

		 @{b}Known Problems!@{ub}

> Most problems that you may experience with TaskBar are due to the
 owner of the window rather that taskbar. I am afraid that some
 applications just do not like other tasks such as TaskBar taking
 control over their windows and fiddling with them.
 There aren't any serious problems, but some windows simply will not
 panel or maximise properly. I am afraid that there is no way around
 this. Fortunately most recent programs that handle windows cleanly
 will work perfectly with TaskBar.

@endnode

